Mapes appears to have had a special employment in the court of the young king Henry‚ after he had been crowned by his father, until his untimely death in 1182, and he shows great affection for the memory of that princc, and speaks leniently of his errore* lt appears by the anecdotes related by himself and by Giraldus Cambrensis that he accompanied king Henry II. in nearly all his progresses. He was with him in Anjou soon after the election of Geoffrey to the archbishopric of York‚ in 1183.† ln 1196 Mapes was appointed archdeacon of Oxford31 from which date we lose sight of him entirely.

Walter Mapes was evidently a man not only of much learning and extensive reading, but of great taste for lighter literature. His mind appears to have been stored with legenda and anecdotos,

and he was universally admired for his ready wit and humour. He speaks of himself as enjoying the reputation of a poet,§ but he gives us no clue to the character of the compositione by which he had entitled himself to this name. His Latin is very unequal;
